{"id":"2203.02828","submitter":"Wei Guo","authors":"Satoshi Yui, Yuan Tang, Wei Guo, Hiromichi Kobayashi, and Makoto\n  Tsubota","title":"Universal anomalous turbulent diffusion in quantum fluids","comments":"7 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.other nlin.CD","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In classical viscous fluids, turbulent eddies are known to be responsible for\nthe rapid spreading of embedded particles. But in an inviscid quantum fluid\nwhere the turbulence is induced by a chaotic tangle of quantized vortices,\ndispersion of the particles is achieved via a non-classical mechanism, i.e.,\ntheir binding to the evolving quantized vortices. However, there is limited\nexisting knowledge on how the vortices diffuse and spread in turbulent quantum\nfluids. Here we report a systematic numerical study of the apparent diffusion\nof vortices in a random vortex tangle in superfluid helium-4 using full\nBiot-Savart simulation. We reveal that the vortices in pure superfluid exhibit\na universal anomalous diffusion (superdiffusion) at small times, which transits\nto normal diffusion at large times. This behavior is found to be caused by a\ngeneric scaling property of the vortex velocity, which should exist in all\nquantum fluids where the Biot-Savart law governs the vortex motion. Our\nsimulation at finite temperatures also nicely reproduces recent experimental\nobservations. The knowledge obtained from this study may form the foundation\nfor understanding turbulent transport and universal vortex dynamics in various\ncondensed-matter and cosmic quantum fluids.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 5 Mar 2022 22:53:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-08"}
