{"id":"2203.02914","submitter":"David Cirauqui","authors":"Maciej Lewenstein, David Cirauqui, Miguel Angel Garcia-March, Guillem\n  Guigo i Corominas, Przemyslaw Grzybowski, Jose R.M. Saavedra, Martin Wilkens,\n  and Jan Wehr","title":"Haake-Lewenstein-Wilkens approach to spin-glasses revisited","comments":"10 pages, 8 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1751-8121/ac9d10","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We revisit the Haake-Lewenstein-Wilkens (HLW) approach to Edwards-Anderson\n(EA) model of Ising spin glass [Phys. Rev. Lett. 55, 2606 (1985)]. This\napproach consists in evaluation and analysis of the probability distribution of\nconfigurations of two replicas of the system, averaged over quenched disorder.\nThis probability distribution generates squares of thermal copies of spin\nvariables from the two copies of the systems, averaged over disorder, that is\nthe terms that enter the standard definition of the original EA order\nparameter, qEA. We use saddle point/steepest descent method to calculate the\naverage of the Gaussian disorder in higher dimensions. This approximate result\nsuggest that qEA >0 at 0 <T <Tc in 3D and 4D. The case of 2D seems to be a\nlittle more subtle, since in the present approach energy increase for a domain\nwall competes with boundary/edge effects more strongly in 2D; still our\napproach predicts spin glass order at sufficiently low temperature. We\nspeculate, how these predictions confirm/contradict widely spread opinions\nthat: i) There exist only one (up to the spin flip) ground state in EA model in\n2D, 3D and 4D; ii) There is (no) spin glass transition in 3D and 4D (2D). This\npaper is dedicated to the memories of Fritz Haake and Marek Cieplak.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 6 Mar 2022 09:19:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-23"}
